 <hr align="left" color="#000000" size="1"/>
 <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">
  <br/>
  In the sign for "
  <b>
   KNIFE
  </b>
  " the right index finger starts with the palm 
  facing backward and moves down and contacts the second knuckle of the left 
  index finger then makes a small backward slicing movement as it continues its 
  downward path.
  <br/>
  <br/>
  <img border="0" height="214" src="/images/knife.9.jpg" width="223"/>
  <img border="0" height="214" src="/images/knife.10.jpg" width="223"/>
  <img border="0" height="214" src="/images/knife.11.jpg" width="223"/>
  <img border="0" height="214" src="/images/knife.12.jpg" width="223"/>
  <br/>
  <font face="Arial">
   <br/>
   The above version of "knife" looks a lot like the sign for "
   <a href="../c/cant.htm">
    CAN'T
   </a>
   " 
  but there are some important differences.
  In the sign for
   <b>
    "can't"
   </b>
   the right hand (if you are right 
	handed) starts palm down, moves downward 
  and whacks the
   <i>
    tip
   </i>
   of the left index finger very quickly.  
  The left index finger bends as the right index finger past in its downward 
  movement.
  </font>
  <br/>
 </p>
 <hr color="#000000" size="1"/>
 <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">
  <a href="/images/knifeversion1.gif">
   Animation: KNIFE (version 1)
  </a>
 </p>
 <hr color="#000000" size="1"/>
 <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">
  <br/>
  In this next version, the knife moves 
  down, contacts the "carrot" and the slices forward along and off of the 
  carrot. As if peeling a carrot.
  <br/>
  <br/>
  KNIFE (version)
  <br/>
  <img border="0" height="215" src="/images/knife.17.jpg" width="225"/>
  <img border="0" height="215" src="/images/knife.18.jpg" width="225"/>
  <img border="0" height="215" src="/images/knife.19.jpg" width="225"/>
  <img border="0" height="215" src="/images/knife.20.jpg" width="225"/>
  <br/>
 </p>
 <hr color="#000000" size="1"/>
 <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">
